      await t.step("step 2", async () => {
        await new Promise(() => {});
      });
    });
  },
});
```
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/29990554/225870259-0e5b5543-02b9-48eb-89e5-0c112c666355.png)

The vast majority of this PR is the prerequisite of refactoring the concurrent-test-step buffer system to Rust. The buffering logic should be easier to reason about. Instead of changing output streaming behaviour based on sanitizers, it just buffers any test result whose output doesn't belong in the current scope and flushes it when a test on the same scope has finished reporting.

This is a performance improvement for **the first run** (no type checking cache--no check_cache_v1 file) for the default behaviour of any sub command that does type checking. This should have a big improvement for CIs.

For example, the following file:

```ts
import $ from "https://deno.land/x/dax@0.30.1/mod.ts";
import { ts } from "https://deno.land/x/ts_morph@17.0.1/mod.ts"

console.log(ts);
console.log($);

const a: string = $;
```

...now type checks in 600ms compared to 2s with no type checking cache.

Closes #18171

Fixes `Deno.inspect` to make an object literal non-compact when an entry has multiple lines in it.

